# v0.7 perf progress vs Rust libs

**Date**: 2026-05-03 · **Branch**: `main` (commits `9e9c3d1` → … → `3ae27e9` (**B0 static-path wire-in**) → `c8cd770` → `46addbd` → `765e027` (**doc → `.cursor/rules/`**) → `0116178` (`on_readable_from_buf`) → `981eb8e` → `c6ccc79` → `bf6ca75` (**buffer-ring substrate**) → `9cf97d0` → `392cf15` (gen-stamping) → `a91413d` (**B0 handler-path wire-in shipped opt-in**) → `cf7f138` (Scheduler wire-in opt-in) → `88ea2f7` (**SO_REUSEPORT per-worker bind for io_uring** -- production pattern from monoio + tokio-uring; fixes the shared-listener-fd kernel race for multi-worker bufring smoke; sustained multi-worker load still hangs from a separate buffer-ring multi-ring interaction bug requiring `IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING` for resolution)).

This note tracks where flare v0.7 stands against the design-0.7
gate (≥ 220 K req/s on flare_mc 4w EPYC, p99.99 ≤ 3.5 ms) and
against the reference Rust libraries (`hyper`, `axum`,
`actix_web`).

The EPYC numbers below are from the v0.6.0 release tag
(`benchmark/results/throughput_mc-vs-rust/`,
2026-04-30T0228-ehsan-dev-c84a119, EPYC 7R32, `wrk2 -t8 -c256
-d30s` calibrated peak). The dev-box numbers are this
worktree's own measurements on a 64-vCPU AWS box (commit
`1b0852d`, same wrk2 calibration).

