## Wire-in 1-worker throughput regression: WHY io_uring 49K < epoll 66K

Same-binary, same-harness A/B (toggling `FLARE_BUFRING_HANDLER`):

| Backend | Req/s (peak) | p99 | p99.99 |
|---|---:|---:|---:|
| io_uring buffer-ring | 49,812 | **2.76 ms** | **3.26 ms** |
| epoll | **65,990** | 3.11 ms | 3.46 ms |

io_uring trades **−32 % peak throughput** for **−11 % p99 / −6 % p99.99**.

Per-request work breakdown (TFB plaintext, kept-alive HTTP/1.1):

| | epoll path | io_uring buffer-ring |
|---|---|---|
| Wait for readiness | 1 `epoll_wait` (batched N events) | 1 `io_uring_enter` (batched CQEs + SQEs) |
| Read bytes | 1 `recv` syscall | **0 syscalls** (kernel push via buffer ring) ✅ |
| Run handler | — | — |
| Write response | 1 `send` syscall | 1 `send` syscall ❌ (still synchronous) |
| Refill kernel buffer | — | **1 `PROVIDE_BUFFERS` SQE** ❌ (extra work per CQE) |
| **Net syscalls/req** | **3** | **~2** + extra SQE bookkeeping |

io_uring saves the recv syscall but adds the per-CQE
`PROVIDE_BUFFERS` refill SQE AND still pays the synchronous
send syscall. On the dev-box at 1-worker, the refill SQE +
in-kernel buffer-ring bookkeeping cost more than the recv
syscall cost it saves. The tail wins because each
`io_uring_enter` does more work per syscall (less context-
switch jitter), but raw throughput regresses.

**Two paths to close the gap (both v0.7.x scope)**:

1. **`submit_send` for the response** — drops the synchronous
   send syscall. `UringReactor.submit_send` already exists and
   is unit-tested. The blocker is per-conn buffer-ownership
   tracking: the response bytes (in `ConnHandle.write_buf`)
   must outlive the in-flight send SQE, but the next request's
   `_serialize_response` would otherwise overwrite them.
   Cleanest fix: per-conn ping-pong write-buffers (write_buf_a
   in flight, write_buf_b for the next response), or a
   reference-count on write_buf bumped on submit_send and
   decremented on the send CQE.

2. **`IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING` (kernel 5.19+)** — drops the
   per-CQE `PROVIDE_BUFFERS` refill entirely. The kernel
   manages a fixed-size ring of buffer entries that recycles
   automatically; userspace only updates a cached_tail pointer
   to advertise new buffers. Bigger registration API change but
   eliminates the SQE pressure on the hot path.

Combined, these would eliminate BOTH the synchronous send AND
the per-CQE refill, dropping io_uring to **~1 syscall/req** vs
epoll's 3 — at which point the throughput trade flips
decisively in io_uring's favour. The current wire-in's tail
win (p99 -11 %, p99.99 -6 %) is direct evidence the io_uring
substrate is fundamentally faster; the throughput regression
is a missing-feature problem, not an architectural one.

## Production io_uring HTTP server patterns (deep dive)

This session burned several iterations re-discovering patterns that
production io_uring HTTP servers (`monoio`, `tokio-uring`,
`glommio`) had already converged on. Captured here so the next
session doesn't make the same mistakes.

### Multi-worker listener: SO_REUSEPORT per-worker, NOT shared fd

* **`monoio`** exposes
  [`ListenerOpts::reuse_port`](https://docs.rs/monoio/latest/monoio/net/struct.ListenerOpts.html)
  in its public API. Multi-worker monoio servers default to
  per-worker SO_REUSEPORT bind.
* **`tokio-uring`** uses thread-per-core with isolated SQ/CQ
  pairs per thread (DESIGN.md: "no work-stealing, tasks remain
  on the thread that spawned them").
* **The Linux io-uring maintainers** have shipped multiple
  multishot accept fixes specifically for the shared-listener
  case (multishot accept overflow handling, double-completion
  bug, execution-context bug -- all on
  lore.kernel.org/io-uring). The shared-listener path is a
  known minefield.

flare's wire-in (`88ea2f7`) now matches this pattern: each
pthread worker calls `bind_reuseport(addr)` to create its OWN
listener; the Scheduler does not bind a listener at all on the
io_uring path (it just probe-binds to validate the addr early).

### Buffer ring API: REGISTER_PBUF_RING (5.19+), not PROVIDE_BUFFERS

Per Linux's own kernel benchmarks
([commit c7fb194](https://github.com/torvalds/linux/commit/c7fb194)):

| Provider mode | NOP test ops/sec |
|---|---:|
| No provided buffers | 30M |
| `IORING_OP_PROVIDE_BUFFERS` (replenish 32) | 16M |
| `IORING_OP_PROVIDE_BUFFERS` (replenish 1) | **10M** |
| `IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING` (replenish 32) | 27M |
| `IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING` (replenish 1) | **27M** |

flare currently uses `IORING_OP_PROVIDE_BUFFERS` with
replenish-1 -- the slowest variant (3x slowdown vs no-buffer).
Switching to `IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING` would give 2.7x
throughput on the buffer-management path AND has simpler
kernel-side bookkeeping (the application updates a cached_tail
pointer to advertise new buffers; no SQE per refill).

### Owned-buffer pattern for `submit_send`

Both `monoio` and `tokio-uring` use an **owned-buffer** pattern
for I/O ops: pass buffer ownership to the kernel during the
operation, get it back on the completion CQE. tokio-uring
defines an `IoBufMut` trait requiring stable memory pointers
via `stable_mut_ptr` so the kernel can safely access the
buffer for the operation's full lifetime.

For flare's send path, this means: per-conn write buffer is
"owned by the kernel" between `submit_send` and the matching
send CQE; the next request's `_serialize_response` cannot
touch it until the CQE arrives. Cleanest implementation:
per-conn ping-pong write buffers (`write_buf_a` in flight,
`write_buf_b` for the next response). monoio's
[zero-copy send PR](https://github.com/bytedance/monoio/pull/386)
shows the matching state machine: lifecycle states
`CompletedMore`, `WaitingMore`, `IgnoredMore` for the multi-CQE
flow of `IORING_OP_SEND_ZC`.

### Concrete next-session work (in priority order)

1. **`IORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING`** -- biggest single perf win
   (2.7x on buffer mgmt path). Likely also resolves the
   multi-worker sustained-load hang because of the simpler
   kernel-side bookkeeping. struct `io_uring_buf_reg` shape
   is in `liburing/man/io_uring_register.2`.
2. **`submit_send` with per-conn ping-pong write buffers** --
   drops the synchronous send syscall on the io_uring path.
3. **EPYC 4w re-bench** -- on production hardware, both fixes
   above are expected to flip the trade in io_uring's favour
   based on published benchmarks of similar Rust servers.

