## Multi-worker hang: WHY 1w bufring works but 2w bufring hangs

Tested on commit `cf7f138` with `FLARE_BENCH_WORKERS=2` +
`FLARE_BUFRING_HANDLER=1`:

| Workload | Result |
|---|---|
| Single-conn 50 keepalive reqs | **50/50 OK** |
| 8 sequential conns × 5 reqs (no sleep) | makes it to conn 3-7, then hangs |
| Same with `sleep(50ms)` between conns | makes it further (conn 7) |
| `wrk2 -t4 -c64 -R20000` for 5s | 48 reqs in 6s, 192 timeouts |

`ss -tnp` after the hang shows server-side fds in CLOSE-WAIT
(peer closed, server didn't process the close). The recv CQE
that should report `res=0` for the FIN never reaches the
worker's dispatch loop.

Same code on the **epoll multi-worker path**
(`FLARE_DISABLE_IO_URING=1`, mc 2w): 99,265 wrk2 requests in
5s, all 8 sequential conns serve 20/20 each. **So the bug is
buffer-ring-specific in the multi-worker configuration**, NOT
a Mojo runtime / Scheduler / Pool issue.

**Most likely root cause**: kernel-level interaction with
multiple multishot accept arms on a SHARED listener fd from
DIFFERENT io_uring rings. When worker A's recv multishot for
fd_N completes (peer FIN), worker A issues `cancel_conn` +
close. Meanwhile worker B may have stale per-fd kernel
structure from when the kernel was deciding which ring to
deliver the original accept to. The cleanup race manifests as
the FIN's CQE being dropped or routed incorrectly.

**Two debug paths for the next session**:

1. **Per-fd ownership tracking**: accept CQE in worker A
   "claims" the fd; worker B (if it ever sees state for it)
   defers. Requires shared state across workers, undoes the
   per-worker-ring isolation.

2. **`SO_REUSEPORT` + per-worker bind**: each worker has its
   OWN listener fd bound to the same port via SO_REUSEPORT.
   Removes the shared-fd interaction entirely; matches what
   tokio-uring / monoio do for multi-worker. flare already has
   `flare/runtime/reuseport.bind_shared`; the wire-in change
   is mechanical (give each worker its own bound listener
   instead of sharing one).

Path #2 is the right architectural answer (matches the rest
of the io_uring HTTP server ecosystem) and is the natural
v0.7.x extension.

